I don't think you'll get into Data 100 if you haven't fulfilled the prereqs, but luckily 165 for 61C is not that far as they just expanded the class by 200 seats and waitlist will process at 6:30 PM.

370 is also not really a real class (it's a seminar with some weekly writing as homework) so I'd definitely recommend seeing which other classes you might be able to get into.

CS 370 is very much a real class, and used by undergraduate TAs and prospective to be cleared to officially TA.  If you want to pursue CS in any pedagogical or teaching role, it is crucial to take this class. :)

I don't think you'll get into Data 100 if you haven't fulfilled the prereqs, but luckily 165 for 61C is not that far as they just expanded the class by 200 seats and waitlist will process at 6:30 PM.

370 is also not really a real class (it's a seminar with some weekly writing as homework) so I'd definitely recommend seeing which other classes you might be able to get into.

I don't think you'll get into Data 100 if you haven't fulfilled the prereqs, but 165 for 61C is also really far down on the waitlist. 370 is also not really a real class (it's a seminar with some weekly writing as homework) so I'd definitely recommend seeing which other classes you might be able to get into.

i'm currently enrolled in CS 70, CS 370, and one breadth class for the fall semester. i'm also on the waitlist for both CS 61C (position 165) & Data 100 (position 63). i don't want to enroll in both classes, but i'm not sure whether it'd be more likely for me to get off the waitlist for 61C or Data 100, which is why i've stayed on both of the waitlists for now (i haven't fulfilled all of the prereqs for Data 100 so even though i could theoretically get into the class according to the 10% rule, i'm not sure if the fact that i haven't fulfilled all the prereqs would prevent me from getting in). would it be better to drop 61C or Data 100? any advice is appreciated. thank you so much :)
